s</span><hr size=1> This is not a tutorial, and more of a pointer/tips thingy. My skills is not very good yet, nor does my design, but I hope I could help a little or two.<br>
<br>
Oh and I must say, this a text heavy post. Perhaps I could draw up a few mechas when I don't feel so lazy <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :rollin --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/roll.gif ALT=":rollin"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
You have been warned <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :evil --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/devil.gif ALT=":evil"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Designing the bestest best mecha</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
1. One thing that most of us ( I think ) is that we doodle something randomly and go from there. It's a good way, especially when the I-feel-like-drawing-but-can't-seems-to-draw symptoms kick in. However, what I will like to do is to first base the design one idea. It could be <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;speed&quot; , &quot;power&quot; , &quot;alien&quot;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> yadayada the list goes on. With the idea set in mind, it would be easier to get the feel (at least for me)<br>
<br>
2. As a famous artist once found out, everything can be broken in geometrical shape. How true those words were! Especially mechas <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
If you observe properly, you will notice even the professional's mecha could be broken down into rectangulars, elipse, cyclinder, pyramid, cone, chocolate wrappers...yadayada. <br>
<br>
So what do we do with the geos u ask? Well if we study on the geos, you will find that each of them would give different feel to the drawing. Let's take an triangle for example. It would give the feel of balance if placed correctly, but also inbalance if turned the other way.  A square is more or less gives u the feeling of a strong base personality, sturdy and yet not openminded or old fashioned.<br>
<br>
What the heck are those you ask. Well basically it's a stupid rant of mine lol. Anyway here's the real one<br>
<br>
Square = Suits military mecha, or standard mecha if you want<br>
Triangle = Best used in speed based mechas, esepcially flying<br>
Round = Stocky, or more organic <br>
Cylinder = Mechanical, like drawing the frames of a mecha<br>
<br>
Try mix-matching those Squares and Rounds together, using different geos for the head and another geos for the leg and torso. Could come up with something ya know<br>
<br>
3. Once you design a mecha, that doesn't really mean you are done with it. You can use something that is called variations and shift-emphasis. The same mecha could look very different if it's weapon system is changed or more armor is added. Or perhaps you wanted a more fast, stealthy type? Experiment with the base 'standard' mecha. You will be surprised by the different types<br>
<br>
Shift-emphasis works like this. A standard mecha looks.....well standard lol. However what if I focus on the arm and make it more big and powerful? Viola! another mecha. How about adding those cool wings I always wanted ? Presto !<br>
<br>
Shift-emphasis and variations are your best friend until you can come up with new ideas <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
4. Spend some free time and do things you wouldn't normally do. Trust me on this. 90% of the times, I would come up with new weird ideas. Exploring new things creates even more eh...new things! <br>
<br>
5. Use back old ideas. Sometimes, the tried and true designs are still the best. That doesn't mean you copy it 100%!! Use that idea and evolve it in another way. Let what if a Gundam looks more Eva like, or perhaps even more of buggish look? You never knew until you drawn them <br>
<br>
6. Have fun while doodling. If you are not having fun... then perhaps you should rest. Put down the pencil, get up and walk around. Come back later when you are refreshed again. Even human need to restart and empty the RAM once in while <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<br>
